It is now usual in English schools to read the classica in suippets‚ partly, l suppose, in order that boys may become acquainted with many authors before they leave school But by following this plan they cannot become intimate with any. One may read Macaulay's essay on Clive with profit even if one ignores all the others; but to read the ninth chapter only of his History of Errylond would not be wise.
